<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
	Privacy manifest for the iOS app. Required by App Store Connect: an
	upload that uses a "required reason" API without declaring it here is
	rejected with ITMS-91053 ("Missing API declaration").

	Every entry below was derived from a grep of the shipping code, not from
	a template — see docs/app-store-submission.md for the audit. The
	MatronNSE extension has no manifest because it links nothing and uses no
	required-reason API; add one there the moment that changes.

	NSPrivacyCollectedDataTypes is deliberately empty (Dan's sign-off,
	2026-07-21). Matron is bring-your-own-server: everything the user sends —
	sign-in identity, messages, attachments — goes only to a journal server
	the user operates, which the developer never sees, so under Apple's
	definition ("collect" = the developer or its partners can access the data
	off-device for longer than needed to service the request) nothing is
	collected. The push and device-linking relays (push.matron.chat) are
	content-blind and forward-and-forget: they hold only an opaque token or
	an app-encrypted box in memory, never stored or logged, so they collect
	nothing either. This must stay in step with the App Privacy answers in
	App Store Connect ("No, we do not collect data from this app") and the
	published privacy policy at matron.chat/privacy.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
	<key>NSPrivacyTracking</key>
	<false/>
	<!--
		No data is shared with data brokers or used to track across apps or
		websites owned by other companies, so this stays empty. Any future
		analytics or ad SDK makes both this and NSPrivacyTracking wrong.
	-->
	<key>NSPrivacyTrackingDomains</key>
	<array/>
	<key>NSPrivacyAccessedAPITypes</key>
	<array>
		<dict>
			<!--
				UserDefaults: appearance setting (MatronAppearance), recent
				/start folders (RecentStartFolders), answered ask-user
				prompts (ChatViewModel), the MatronDebug flag, and the Mac
				window defaults. All of it is read and written through
				`UserDefaults.standard` — app-local only. No app-group suite
				is used in shipping code (only tests construct suites), which
				is exactly what CA92.1 covers.
			-->
			<key>NSPrivacyAccessedAPIType</key>
			<string>NSPrivacyAccessedAPICategoryUserDefaults</string>
			<key>NSPrivacyAccessedAPITypeReasons</key>
			<array>
				<string>CA92.1</string>
			</array>
		</dict>
		<dict>
			<!--
				FileManager.attributesOfItem(atPath:) in SearchSchema, which
				asserts NSFileProtectionComplete on the search index. It reads
				.protectionKey rather than a timestamp, and it's gated to
				`#if os(iOS) && !targetEnvironment(simulator)` — so this is
				declared defensively: Apple's static check flags the call
				site, and the file it inspects is inside our own container,
				which is precisely what C617.1 describes. (The Mac manifest
				omits this: that code path is iOS-only.)
			-->
			<key>NSPrivacyAccessedAPIType</key>
			<string>NSPrivacyAccessedAPICategoryFileTimestamp</string>
			<key>NSPrivacyAccessedAPITypeReasons</key>
			<array>
				<string>C617.1</string>
			</array>
		</dict>
	</array>
	<key>NSPrivacyCollectedDataTypes</key>
	<array/>
</dict>
</plist>
